I see many bright boys and girls who have no desires to progress because they don’t see any future beyond scavenging through rubbish for outdated or unwanted clothing and watching their parents on the streets for a quick meal. “I love film and I am convinced it can change the way people think,” says Naima Mohamed, once a leader of the young people and still a committed, driven film maker.

“Simo is an important film about the gritty reality of life for young people in Somaliland. We all need to help each other, even across oceans and national divides. That is what Simo is all about.”

Stefan Kartsberg, Managing Director of the SDUT, says: “Distanced from the UN-led peace process in Somalia between successive governments and extremists since the late 80s, Somaliland has successfully charted its own political course. There are parallels here for United Nations reform under the leadership of the UN General Secretary Secretary Ban Ki Moon.

“The turbulent situation in Somalia has not strongly affected Somaliland. Simo demonstrates the power that film-making has to reach beyond regions and borders, to confront crucial issues locally, and beyond.
